\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par Political Structure:}{\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  The fists of Xlevan have grown a lot, even since Xlevan\rquote 
s death. Due to its size, it is difficult to place one leader in charge of all Fist of Xlevan efforts. As a result, the fists of Xlevan have two leaders. A commander, in charge of the fists field armies and city guards, and an overseer, who
 presides over the trading and administration of the fists domain. Beneath the overseer is a council of master merchants, and beneath the commander of course are his captains. 
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Rob and I discussed the very important question: if the Fists are so strong, why don\rquote t they just take Lu\rquote Tamohr?  Personally, I am against starting with a clan which screams \'93We Rule\'94
 from day one.  So I would suggest a little flaw to their dominance, which will affect the ability to travel into their lands as well.  I would like mu
ch of the vast lands held by the fists to be very sparsely populated, and difficult.  Swamps, remote hills, barely livable plains and deserts.  These vast lands are a strain to hold, but they represent a buffer to the Fists heartlands, and for strategic r
e
asons will not be abandoned.  This ties up the resources of the Fists, making them more vulnerable and less of a threat to the others, and allows us to build smaller sites - border posts with just a few soldiers and a farm, tiny dreary scattering of mud-h
uts in the swamps\'85 and bitter officers trained to the glory of the Fists but placed in what they see as honourless exile guarding a heap of rocks or a mudpond.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\b\f38\cf2\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
[Mark: The logistics alone of fighting over a long distance is a good start as to why they can\rquote t dominate the whole isle.  Without a steady route of supply from Cora\rquote 
Lyst to wherever they are fighting, the forces are soon forced back unless 1. They have overwhelming numbers 2. They have overwhelming skill.  However, if the clan has plans of dominance,
 giving them shoddy lands to hold is probably not a good way to sate their hunger for battle, conquest etc.  Perhaps if they had some decent land, they might not want to grab more so much.  Just a suggestion.  Also, if they are governed by two people, the
 opposing opinions between them could be reason to stop them from invading.  Perhaps this is a source of conflict within the Fists, giving them no clear direction.  Not sure if this is what you had in mind for them, however.
\par 
\par Also, the structure of the clan sounds cool, but consider the logistics of this when making up the clan with actual players.  Two leaders for a start can be somewhat interesting \endash 
 introduces a whole new level of diplomacy within a clan which might actually mirror what I am talking about with people with opposing ideas \endash 
 stick a hippie and a warrior leading the clan, and they would fight each other more than others.  I will speak of this more in future, however.]
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What they are up to when the mud opens:
\par }{\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 As the lands controlled by the fists of Xlevan are not opened as yet, it is impossible to fully introduce the fists of Xlevan. What I would suggest would be the following:
\par 
\par An emissary sent to Ru\rquote Psarn, to search out new followers, but not to conscript the
m yet. To explain the players inability to join the clan or venture to the territories of the fists I would suggest that when we open, the fists have just instigated a blockade, angered by something that the silver tongues have done. So players trying to 
venture to Cora\rquote Lyst and its territories would reach a line of soldiers, telling them to turn back as they are under orders.
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I have a little problem with this blockade, but I expect the reason will be clearer by and by.  If there is to be a conflict betwee
n the Silver Tongues and the Fists this early in the game (although it fits well with the theme) I want it 1) not to the point of a threat of war breaking out and 2) over a specific and easily solved matter, deadlocked out of reasons of diplomacy and conv
enience rather than a real conflict.
\par 
\par Why?
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1) \tab}}\pard \qj \fi-283\li283\ri0\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec\pnb0\pni0\pnfs24\pnstart1\pnindent283\pnhang{\pntxta ) }}\faauto\ls1\adjustright\rin0\lin283\itap0 {
\i\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 If the game starts at the point of where a war can start, we may easily become manipulated into the point where we have to start the war or make an illogic imm decision that there will be no war.  So, the sit
uation on start-up in my point of view has to be firm, stable, conflicts should be visible but not over-powering.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2) \tab}}\pard \qj \fi-283\li283\ri0\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec\pnb0\pni0\pnfs24\pnstart1\pnindent283\pnhang{\pntxta ) }}\faauto\ls1\adjustright\rin0\lin283\itap0 {
\i\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I would like to have the option to solve this conflict, and I would like to have that option open for layer participation.  Careful nego
tiations, some parties with polite mingling, a few exchanges of gifts and concessions\'85 and the conflict will be solved.  This can take as much time as we like, and be done with the moment the cities are ready to open.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\b\f38\cf2\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 [Mark: I would also be hesistant to put Lu\rquote 
Tamohr upon the brink of total war when we open.  I like the idea of a blockade per se, but would suggest something less inflammatory for the reason.  Perhaps the bandits in Falsta Tandar are being particularly active and the road is closed until they
 are subdued.  With the amount of piracy and the like brought up later in this doc, it doesn\rquote 
t seem to be an unpopular idea.  If the Silver Tongues must be involved, perhaps they are unimpressed that the Fists are not keeping the road clear for trade withi
n the cities, hence cutting them off.  They could think the Fists are doing in intentionally to starve them, even though Cora\rquote Lyst suffers also.  With this, representatives could meet in Ru\rquote 
Psarn to clear the air, discover the truth (that the Fists plan to sort it out) and go merrily on their way.  Could have players doing part of the talks if we wanted.]
