Tyl, where they control the islands trade in minerals, ores and metals. Their domain does not stretch very far, encompassing only a variety of mines throughout the Malandrin ranges and a few small towns southwest of Cora\rquote 
Tyl. The Silver Tongues rely on the highway to Cora\rquote Lyst to trade most of their goods, even with Il\rquote Cora\rquote Dvan which they ship from Cora\rquote 
Lyst. The Silver Tongues are a very rich clan, but do not possess the armies that the fists possess, and have desires on riches rather then conquer. Cora\rquote Tyl is pretty much impregnable which is why no one has successfully conquered it.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Political Structure:}{\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  The Silver Tongues have a single leader, who is responsible for the guidance of Silver Tongue policy in Lu\rquote 
Tamohr. Beneath him is his chancellor who presides over Cora\rquote Tyl, and beneath them a council of master merchants. Th
e Silver Tongues also have a commander, and although he does not command armies of the size of the fists, he is still an excellent commander. 
\par 
\par }{\i\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What the Silver Tongues lack in size, they make up in defensability.  The \'93heart\'94 of their power is the very def
ensible city, with the mines close.  They may have to tighten their belts a bit in a siege, but strategists that they are, there are large stores of food within their walls.  This frees larger parts of their troops, in case of an armed conflict, and the t
e
rrain they have to defend is while smaller, also one that consistently gives defenders the higher ground, and will make a strategic retreat a battle each step of the way, less than a headless run trying not to be cut off from the capital, as a retreat in 
the areas of the Fists will be.  This way terrain balances might, and keeps the two military powers both in check.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\b\f38\cf2\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
[Mark: Domain sounds fine, it is what I expected.  Once again though, the actual structure is something we have to consider from a point of vi
ew of filling the roles with actual players.  Would a council of merchants actually be able to be filled?  It would be quite cool if you could only hold a high Silver Tongue rank if you had the merchant spec, actually.  However, what is the function of th
i
s merchant council?  Control trade from and within the city?  Seven is a lot of people to reach an agreement, unless democracy rules and they can vote to resolve issues.  Seems to just make a council to talk lots and accomplish little in my eyes.  Not to 
say it\rquote s bad, I like the idea, just raising how it would work practically.]
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
